Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps

The facility has a number of safeguards that are used to protect personnel and property from the hazards of the covered processes. These safeguards were either originally constructed in the unit or implemented as a recommendation from a PHA, audit, or other avenue. These safeguards are examined during a PHA for their adequacy in detecting, preventing and/or mitigating potential hazards of the process. If the PHA team determines that the safeguards do not adequately protect against a particular hazard, corrective actions are recommended.

As part of the PHA study, potential hazards and their safeguards are examined in a rigorous, methodical fashion for a variety of scenarios. The primary focus is on prevention of release. The following are examples of safeguards designed for prevention of the identified potential hazard:
¿ Excessive pressure: high pressure alarms, pressure relief valves, thermal relief valves, piping/flange/equipment pressure ratings, water separation facilities, and safety valves;
¿ Excessive temperature: high temperature alarms, manual shutdowns, and automatic shutdowns;
¿ Low temperature: insulation and heating;
¿ Excessive flow: high flow alarms, "fail safe" position control valves, and pressure safety valves;
¿ Low flow or no flow: low flow alarms, recycle streams, shutdown systems, and check valves;
¿ High and low levels: high and low level alarms and shutdown systems;
¿ Contamination: analyzers, check valves, and standardized utility connections.
¿ Explosions: furnace instrumentation, control of ignition sources;
¿ Loss of containment: isolation valves, proper material selection for corrosion and temperature, avoidance of dead legs, periodic inspection, proper water draws and sampling
